\f2\fs32 \
   <term>Timing Gears, Camshaft, and Valve Mechanism</term>\
\
In order for a diesel engine to operate, all of its components must perform their functions at very precise intervals in relation to the motion of the piston. To accomplish this, a component called a camshaft is used. Figure 9 illustrates a camshaft and camshaft drive gear. Figure 2 and Figure 3 illustrate the location of a camshaft in a large overhead cam diesel engine. A camshaft is a long bar with egg-shaped eccentric lobes, one lobe for each valve and fuel injector (discussed later). Each lobe has a follower as shown on Figure 10. \
\pard\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_Ps::0>
